ARP(8)                         System Manager's Manual                     ARP(8)

NAME
       arp - manipulate the system ARP cache

SYNOPSIS
       arp [-vn] [-H type] [-i if] -a [hostname]
       arp [-v] [-i if] -d hostname [pub]
       arp [-v] [-H type] [-i if] -s hostname hw_addr [temp] [nopub|pub|trail]
       arp [-vnD] [-H type] [-i if] -f [filename]

DESCRIPTION
       Arp manipulates or displays the kernel's IPv4 network neighbour
       cache. It can add entries to the table, delete one, or display
       the current content.

       ARP stands for Address Resolution Protocol, which is used to
       find the media access control address of a network neighbour
       for a given IPv4 Address.

OPTIONS
       -a [hostname], --all [hostname]
              Display entries of the specified hosts or all hosts if
              no hostname is given. Output uses BSD format.

       -e     Display entries in default (Linux) style with fixed
              columns.

       -d hostname, --delete hostname
              Remove an ARP cache entry for the given hostname.

       -D, --use-device
              Instead of a hw_addr, the given argument is the name
              of an interface. arp will use the MAC of that interface
              for the table entry. This is best used in combination
              with -s to set up a proxy ARP entry.

       -H type, -t type
              When setting or reading the ARP cache, this selects
              which class of entries it should look for. The default
              value is "ether" (IEEE 802.3 10Mbps Ethernet).

       -i If, --device If
              Select an interface. When dumping the ARP cache only
              entries matching the specified interface will be printed.

       -s hostname hw_addr, --set hostname
              Manually create an ARP address mapping entry for host
              hostname with hardware address set to hw_addr. The
              format of the hardware address is dependent on the
              hardware class, but for Ethernet it is 6 hex bytes
              separated by colons.

              The following modifiers may optionally follow hw_addr:

              temp   The entry will not be permanently stored.

              pub    The entry will be published (proxy ARP).

              nopub  The entry will not be published.

              trail  Trailer encapsulation (historical, not used).

       -f [filename], --file [filename]
              Similar to -s, but this time the address info is taken
              from the file. The name of the data file is very often
              /etc/ethers, but this is not official. If no filename
              is specified /etc/ethers is used as default.

              The file format is simple; it only contains ASCII text
              lines with a hostname and a hardware address separated
              by whitespace, optionally followed by "temp" or "pub".

       -n, --numeric
              Shows numerical addresses instead of trying to determine
              symbolic host names.

       -v, --verbose
              Tell the user what is going on by being verbose.

       -V, --version
              Display version information.

       -h, --help
              Display a help message and exit.

EXAMPLES
       arp
              Display the ARP cache in default format.

       arp -a
              Display the ARP cache in BSD format.

       arp -n
              Display the ARP cache with numerical addresses.

       arp -d 192.168.1.1
              Delete the entry for 192.168.1.1.

       arp -s 192.168.1.1 00:11:22:33:44:55
              Create a permanent ARP entry.

       arp -s 192.168.1.1 00:11:22:33:44:55 temp
              Create a temporary ARP entry.

       arp -D -s 192.168.1.1 eth0 pub
              Create a proxy ARP entry using eth0's MAC.

       arp -i eth0
              Display ARP entries for eth0 only.

       arp -f /etc/ethers
              Read entries from /etc/ethers.

SEE ALSO
       route(8), ifconfig(8), netstat(8), arping(8)

